06205nam a22008055i 9780774828192DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748281927 a10.59962/97807748281922doi  a(DE-B1597)661459  a(OCoLC)895341211  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aPOL0070002bisacsh00aTerritorial Pluralism :bManaging Difference in Multinational States /ced. by Karlo Basta, Richard Simeon, John McGarry. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (364 p.) :b11 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEthnicity and Democratic Governance00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tConceptual and Normative Dimensions -- tTerritorial Pluralism -- tA Conceptual and Normative Analysis of Territorial Pluralism -- tCaught in the Minority Trap -- tEmpirical and Comparative Dimensions -- tIs Federalism like Snow, and Is It Exportable? -- tTerritorial Autonomy in Nationally Divided Societies -- tSustaining Territorial Pluralism -- tTerritorial Pluralism in Spain -- tBelgium and the Crisis of Governability, 2007–11 -- tLand and Citizenship in Nigerian Ethnofederalism -- tEthnic Territory, Land Tenure, and Citizenship in Africa -- tConsociational Theory, Self-Determination Disputes, and Territorial Pluralism -- tThe Two Shadows of Empire and Still-Born Federalism in China -- tConclusion -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTerritorial pluralism is a form of political autonomy designed to accommodate national, ethnic, or linguistic differences within a state. It has the potential to provide for the peaceful, democratic, and just management of difference. But given traditional concerns about state sovereignty, nation-building, and unity, how realistic is it to expect that a state's authorities will agree to recognize and empower distinct substate communities? Territorial Pluralism answers this question by examining a wide variety of cases, including developing and industrialized states and democratic and authoritarian regimes. Drawing on examples of both success and failure, contributors analyze specific cases to understand the kinds of institutions that emerge in response to demands for territorial pluralism, as well as their political effects. With identity conflicts continuing to have a major impact on politics around the globe, they argue that territorial pluralism remains a legitimate and effective means for managing difference in multinational states.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCultural pluralismxPolitical aspectsvCase studies. 0aCultural pluralismxPolitical aspects. 0aFederal governmentvCase studies. 0aFederal government. 0aGroup identityxPolitical aspectsvCase studies. 0aGroup identityxPolitical aspects. 0aRegionalismvCase studies. 0aRegionalism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh1 aBachvarova, Mira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBasta, Karlo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBasta, Karlo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBerman, Bruce J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColino, César, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEjobowah, John Boye, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHombrado, Angustias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeating, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKraus, Peter A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc